To configure Apache Airflow to support Azure Active Directory (Azure AD) Single Sign-On (SSO) tokens, you need to set up the necessary configurations in your Airflow environment. This typically involves configuring the Airflow web server to use an OAuth2 provider, such as Azure AD, for authentication.

Here's a step-by-step guide to configure Apache Airflow for Azure AD SSO:

### Step 1: Install Required Packages

First, ensure you have the necessary packages installed. You will need the `apache-airflow-providers-microsoft-azure` package for Azure integration and `apache-airflow-providers-http` for OAuth2 support.

```bash
pip install apache-airflow-providers-microsoft-azure apache-airflow-providers-http
```

### Step 2: Configure Airflow Web Server

Update your `airflow.cfg` file to include the necessary configurations for OAuth2 authentication.

```ini
[webserver]
auth_backend = airflow.api.auth.backend.default

[api]
auth_backend = airflow.api.auth.backend.default

[auth_backend]
auth_provider_xcom_backend = airflow.providers.http.backends.oauth_provider.OAuthProvider

[oauth_provider]
client_id = YOUR_AZURE_AD_CLIENT_ID
client_secret = YOUR_AZURE_AD_CLIENT_SECRET
authorize_url = https://login.microsoftonline.com/YOUR_TENANT_ID/oauth2/v2.0/authorize
token_url = https://login.microsoftonline.com/YOUR_TENANT_ID/

The first time I saw the word “derivative” was in a review of a movie I was dying to see. The reviewer said the movie was “derivative” and I thought, “Oh, that sounds good.” I was in my early teens and I had no idea what the word meant. I thought it meant something like “riveting.” I thought it meant the movie was so good that it was the source from which all other movies flowed.

I was wrong.

I was also wrong about the movie. It was terrible.

But I learned a new word that day. And I learned that words can be deceiving. Just because a word sounds like it means one thing, doesn’t mean it actually does.

So, if you’re ever tempted to use a word you don’t know the meaning of, just remember: it might not mean what you think it means. And you might end up looking like a fool.

Or, you know, you could just look it up. That works too.
